		<lb n="7"/><l met="hexameter" n="7"><w lemma="ὅσος">ὅσσα</w> <w lemma="καί">καὶ</w> <w lemma="οἷος">οἷα</w> <w lemma="πόρω">πόρεν</w> <w lemma="γέρας">γέρα</w> <w lemma="πατρίς">πατρίδι</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῖς</w> <w lemma="ἐπί">ἐπὶ</w> <w lemma="πᾶς">π<supplied reason="lost">ᾶσιν</supplied></w></l>
		<lb n="8"/><l met="pentameter" n="8"><w lemma="καί">καὶ</w> <w lemma="ὅδε">τόδε</w> <w lemma="μετρέω">μετρείσθω</w> <w lemma="σύνειμι">ξυνὸν</w> <w lemma="ἔρεισμα">ἔρεισμα</w> <w lemma="θόλος">θ<unclear reason="damage">ό</unclear><supplied reason="lost">λου</supplied></w>.</l>
		</lg>
		</div>

      <div type="apparatus">
        <head>Apparatus</head>
        <p>There are no significant differences between the modern copies. In line 8, for <foreign lang="grc">ξυνὸν</foreign>, <title level="m">AP</title> has <foreign lang="grc">κοῖλον</foreign>. The Byzantine copyist perhaps chose to 'improve' the text, and wrote <foreign lang="grc">κοινὸν</foreign> which was subsequently corrupted to <foreign lang="grc">κοῖλον</foreign> (as editors since Boeckh have conjectured); but see commentary, <xref type="eAla-text" n="V.8">V.8</xref>.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="translation">
        <head>Translation</head>
        <ab>The light of virtue shines even for dead men, who, undertaking many labours for their country, established general benefits. The saying fits Asklepiodotos, for whom this city has dedicated this statue as for a founder.</ab>
        <ab>Long time wears away even stone; but the fame of Asklepiodotos' virtues is immortal, the number and kind of privileges which he obtained for his country. In addition to all these, let this adjacent structure of the vaulted chamber be counted as well.</ab>
      </div>

      <div type="commentary">
        <head>Commentary</head>
        <p>For Asklepiodotos see also <xref type="inscription" n="54" href="110069">11.69</xref>; see discussion at <xref type="eAla-text" n="V.8">V.8</xref> following.</p>
        
	  </div>
		
		
